en","1136":"1136","1200":"1200","1132":"1132","1163":"1163","1184":"1184","1162":"1162","Abt 1160":"circa 1160","1160":"1160","1207":"1207","Toledo, Castilla, La Mancha, Spain":"Toledo, Castilla-La Mancha, Spanje","Spain":"Spanje"},"en":{"Abt 1160–":"about 1160–Deceased","1160–Male":"1160–Deceased","1162–Male":"1162–Deceased","1163–Female":"1163–Deceased","1184–1207":"1184–1207","1132–Male":"1132–Deceased","1136–Female":"1136–Deceased","1136":"1136","1200":"1200","1132":"1132","1163":"1163","1184":"1184","1162":"1162","Abt 1160":"about 1160","1160":"1160","1207":"1207","Toledo, Castilla, La Mancha, Spain":"Toledo, Castilla-La Mancha, Spain","Spain":"Spain","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Garcia","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jesus, Carlos, Luis, Francisco, Pedro, Miguel, Jorge, Mario, Raul, Roberto, Ramon, Rafael.  Portuguese Wenceslao, Joao, Paulo, Catarina, Albeiro, Ligia, Godofredo, Lidio, Wenseslao, Adao, Afonso.","Spanish (<b>García</b>) and Portuguese: from a medieval personal name of uncertain origin. It is normally found in medieval records in the Latin form <i>Garsea</i>, and may well be of pre-Roman origin, perhaps akin to Basque <i>(h)artz</i> ‘bear’. This is the most common surname in Spain and also one of the most common surnames elsewhere in Spanish-speaking world. In the US, where it is also found among Native Americans (mainly Pueblos in NM), it is the sixth most frequent surname. Compare   De Garcia  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Grassia","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Angelo, Amedeo, Maurizio, Pasquale, Rocco, Salvatore.","Italian: from a metathesized form of the personal name<i>Garsia</i>, from Spanish <i>García</i> (see   Garcia  )."]},{"name":"Arcia","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Alberto, Francisco, Arturo, Dagoberto, Enrique, Jose, Ramiro, Adalberto, Aleida, Alejandro, Alfredo, Amalia.","Hispanic: probably an altered form of Spanish <b>García</b> (see   Garcia  )."]},{"name":"Garcie","meanings":["Altered form, under the French influence in LA, of Spanish <b>García</b> (see   Garcia  ). This form of the surname of Spanish origin is also found in southern France.","Spanish (Ávila): variant of <b>García</b> (see   Garcia  )."]},{"name":"Garcilazo","meanings":["Hispanic (mainly Mexico and Argentina): altered form of Spanish (Valencia) <b>Garcilaso</b>, a compound of the personal name <i>Garci</i> (a short form of <i>García</i>, see   Garcia  ) and the nickname <i>laso</i> ‘weak, exhausted’."]},{"name":"Gacia","meanings":["Hispanic: altered form of Spanish <b>García</b> (see   Garcia  )."]},{"name":"Garsia","meanings":["Hispanic: altered form of   Garcia  ."]},{"name":"Gracia","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Carlos, Juan, Manuel, Francisco, Jesus, Luis, Guadalupe, Mario, Pedro, Javier, Jorge.","Spanish; Catalan (<b>Gràcia</b>): from a short form of the Christian religious epithet <i>de la Gracia</i>, meaning ‘of mercy’ and forming part of the Marian name <i>Maria de la Gracia</i> ‘(Holy) Mary of Grace’, from Spanish <i>gracia</i>, Catalan <i>gràcia</i> ‘grace, mercy’.","In some cases possibly also an altered form of Spanish <b>García</b> (see   Garcia  )."]},{"name":"De Garcia","meanings":["Spanish and Galician (<b>De García</b>); Portuguese: patronymic from Spanish and Galician <b>García</b> and Portuguese   Garcia  , with the preposition <i>de</i> ‘of’."]},{"name":"Garces","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jorge, Carlos, Juan, Jose, Manuel, Cesar, Rafael, Luis, Fernando, Gustavo, Javier, Mario.  Portuguese Albeiro, Paulo.","Spanish; Catalan (<b>Garcés</b>); Portuguese (<b>Garcês</b>): patronymic from the personal name <i>García</i> (see   Garcia  )."]},{"name":"Garzia","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Mario, Alfredo, Ernestina, Fernando, Juan, Pedro, Ricardo.  Italian Angelo, Antonio, Ciro, Corra